The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
 Friday, May 07, 2004 NATION BRIEFS																																												New Delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court on Thursday ordered that a public notice be issued to all schools, including unaided recognised public schools, on the practice of forcing children and their parents to face interviews for admission to pre-primary classes.																																												
	ch of Justices Dalveer Bhandari and R.C. Jain asked the director of education of the state government to publish the notice in Times of India, Hindustan Times and Nav Bharat Times seeking assistance of the schools on this important question of larger public importance. The next hearing is on May 21.																																												New Delhi: The CBI has registered six cases against 22 officials who allegedly used fake caste certificates to get government jobs, reports our correspondent. The agency said the accused were appointed against vacancies for Scheduled Tribe candidates. The cases were registered on the orders of Delhi High Court in a civil writ petition filed by an office superintendent with the National of India, Chandreswar Prasad. In his petition, Prasad had alleged that many persons from Bihar had obtained employment under the Scheduled Tribe category in the Delhi Development Authority, the municipal corporation, the New Delhi Municipal Council and the All India Institute of Medical Sciences, besides schools and colleges in the city. The high court had observed that if the submissions of the petitioner were true, it was a serious encroachment on the rights of deserving beneficiaries.																																												 Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court on Thursday vacated its stay on investigations into the FIR lodged by the Maharashtra government against US-based author James Laine and Oxford Printing Press for publishing derogatory references to Shivaji in a history book. A bench of Justices S. Radhakrishna and R.S. Mohite allowed police to probe the matter in three months and submit a report to the court.
